 @G[c3 stills_61.png]@L 
		@H Historical Background @L
		Syracusae has been inhabited by Greeks and ruled by their tyrants since its establishment as a Greek colony in 734 BC. The locals kept their Hellenic cultural ties, and the city-state was mostly prosperous in the centuries prior to rise of Rome and Carthage, becoming the most powerful Doric Greek settlement in Magna Graecia. @L@L
		This prosperity came to an end when these two ancient superpowers struggled for control of the island of Sicily and its largest city. The siege of Syracusae proved grueling for the Romans, but gave them valuable insights into siege warfare, given the massive Syracusan fortifications and war machines, some of them designed by the famed Archimedes. @L@L
		As with many other things, Romans learned the art of siege craft and use of war machines from the Greeks. Greeks were very fond of using scorpions, a precursor to the medieval ballista, which use a torsion engine. Power was accumulated by ropes and animal sinew in its mechanism, like a medieval crossbow, and could launch large spear projectiles. @L@L
		Other torsion engines such as catapults would also be popular, even Alexander the Great used a lot of these contraptions during his conquests. Due to the nature of these machines, they were expensive to make and maintain and were slow to transport. Even so, Roman armies would often have siege as part of their baggage train and would often be vital. Sometimes siege engines would also be used in field battles but this use was much rarer. @L@L
		Other siege weapons would often be built on site near the city that was being besieged including ladders, siege towers, ramps of earth, battering rams, and protective shields. These would often be covered with animal hide to prevent fires. One neglected use of the siege tower is that it could be used as an elevated skirmishing platform to sweep the enemy walls from a higher position making it unsafe for defenders to man the walls. Only in the final assault would the towers be used to directly access enemy walls. @L@L
		
		@G[c3 instructions icon.png]	
		@H Instructions @L
		Governor, the Second Punic War is in full swing. Rome has just conquered and sacked the city of Syracusae so your task will be to rebuild and fortify it against the Carthaginians who are surely going to attempt to take it back. The terrain should prove decisive in coming battles, especially if you use the high ground to set up defenses from which your soldiers can attack approaching enemies. @L@L
		Do not neglect the economic situation. Syracusae does not have abundant farmland, but the climate is well-suited for growing olives. Olives and olive oil are extremely profitable if traded in bulk, as they are a Roman culinary staple. The Roman Republic has depleted her stocks of oil, meaning that you can expect several requests for this resource. @L@L
		Do not underestimate the enemy governor, they will likely throw everything thay can muster to take back the city. @L@L
		
		@H Edicts @L
		@Oil @Shortages - Rome will ask for olives and oil in high quantities as time goes on. Prices for these goods are higher but other goods are not as valuable. @L@L
		@Carthaginian @Blockade - Sea trade routes have low reliability, as ships tend to get lost at sea while taking irregular routes to avoid the blockade and may, despite these measures, still be captured by the enemy. Building a lighthouse will help alleviate these issues. @L@L
		@Dry @Climate - Gardens, trees, paths and most parks are unavailable for this assignment. @L@L
		
		@H Additional Information @L 
		@L There are 3 invasion points; these are only on exposed edges of the map, though never on entry and exit points directly.@L@L The empire map is bit more fleshed out but not comprehensive by any means. @L
		As is customary, from a historical perspective you should start with a pre-built/ruined city, but few players would like that. It will be up to you to build everything from scratch. @L
		If you wish to train and equip legionaries, you will need an armory to cart weapons from warehouses to your barracks with a road connection. @L@L
		@H Persistent Events @L
		Grand Temple to Mercury unlocks plaza. Subsidies, lasting until 10 prosperity rating, give 100 dn. per month. Workshops only unlock after the subsidy expires. Due to game limitations, starting prices for goods will be adjusted after 1 in-game month has passed. @L@L@L@L

