		@H Historical Background @L
		Romans were generally considered poor sailors, which is counterintuitive considering their future control over so many seas. @L@L
		As with land armies, the Roman navy did learn from their defeats and mistakes and developed new designs and tactics to counter their enemies. @L@L
		Ship combat would often revolve around a small complement of marines for boarding actions and defense, while most of the capability would be centered around war machines and skirmishers. @L@L
		This benefited the Greeks and Carthage who had long naval traditions. Romans developed rams and boarding bridges to turn naval combat into melee fighting which much more suited their capabilities. @L@L
		Most ships of the time would be powered mainly by oars since wind power was often unreliable. Ships had sails but could not be used in all circumstances. @L@L
